From: jwiegand@manny.eng.temple.edu (Don't Panic!)
Subject: Re: Size of NT kernel (was Re: NT vs. Linux)
Date: 21 Aug 93 23:49:14 GMT

In article <250j7g$hqe@charm.magnus.acs.ohio-state.edu> tabaer@magnus.acs.ohio-state.edu (Troy A. Baer) writes:
>Is it just me, or was the claim on the "checklist" that NT's kernel is
>only 50K a little bogus-sounding?  I'm sorry, that's almost impossible,
>especially from MS.  (Then again, they're loading drivers dynamically,
>so that does cut kernel size.  Still...)
>
Pardon me? COMMAND.COM is 52925 bytes! That's (over) 51K.
As for the memory required, I have heard it takes 16M to fire it up
before you run anything. Excuse me, but I don't want to buy $1500 in
ram just to run a $150 operating system.
To say that NT's networking is stable is also a joke. This is the
company whose ``mission critical'' Windows for Workgoups has the 
unfortunate habit of losing files in the ether (see the current
Byte). Network managers (as noted in Lan Times) are wondering
how on earth this turkey will fly over the network.
MicroSquish is the company whose networking operating system is widely
regarded as inferior to the leading Novell Netware (Lan Times).

That little ``release'' is nothing more than another volley in the
MS disinformation/publicity campaign.

jim "reality check" wiegand
>+--------------------+---------------------------------------------------+

