From: ashley@cco.caltech.edu (Allen M. Ashley)
Subject: How are the Linux Packages put Together?
Date: 22 Aug 1993 00:01:23 GMT

With the recent concern over copyright I have been curious about
how the various packages are put together, and how they get put up
on, say, tsx-11 and sunsite. As I  understand it, Linux is the product
of a number of volunteers essentially working independently. By Linux
I mean the whole package including the FSF parts and the kernel, and
anything else that might comprise one of the packages.

When a new version of, say, dosemu comes out, I suppose it is put
up onto one of the sites. How is it determined what parts of that
package are to go into the overall package that is labelled SLS1.03
for example. When there is a package of that name on tsx-11 how does
it get over to sunsite? How could it be that the two versions might not
be the same, and some differences might persist for over a week?

If someone is selling Linux packaged, and presumably making enough
profit to continue in that endeavor, how can that effort be reconciled
with a free offering? Somewhere I think I remember reading that the
offering on tsx-11 might not be identical to that sold in the bundled
disk form.

In the two packaged versions I have downloaded I have found little
problems that would have been found if anyone had tested out the
package after putting it up for distribution. That worries me.


------------------------------

