From: jwiegand@manny.eng.temple.edu (Don't Panic!)
Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: 22 Aug 93 00:59:03 GMT

In article <930820201354.23255@world> brileary@world.std.com (Brian Leary) writes:
>A few neutral observations in this subject:
Yeah, right!
>Observation #1:
>Making fun and degrading remarks about Windows users is fashionable in
>the linux groups. Linux users have the moronic idea that they must be
>somehow mentally and morally superior to the rest of the world. Snide
>remarks about how stupid and gullible Winodws users are are all but
>uncommon in the linux groups.
Gee, I wonder why noone mades snide remarks about X users?
>Observation #2:
>The above is mainly due to the strong SHEEP MENTALITY running in the
>linux community. Few if any linux users have their own mind, After
>all, why bother? It's easier to just echo what a master sheep has
>said. This is obvious in their "rebuttals" to the check list that was
>posted here. Each one just echoes the other -- all of them asserted
>that linux has QIC-80 support, just because the first one said so,
>even though linux HAS NO QIC-80 SUPPORT, nor is likely to have it any
>time soon.

One thing at a time. No one put a gun to my head and said "Run Linux
or Die". I started using it when it first came out and I heard about
it on comp.os.minix. It wasn't really useful, then, so your "sheep"
comment doesn't really make any sense. Linux is, and always will be,
a free Unix.

About QIC80 support: there ARE drivers out there, you just have to
be brave to use them. Most of the problems with QIC80 drives come
from the fact that the hardware design is an incomprehensible
piece of garbage that depended on the faults of DOS. Real computers
use SCSI.

>But that's not all, there is also the LYNCH MOB MENTALITY. After
>hearing about how dum and gullible we are for two years, as soon as an
>objective comparison that shows that linux is not the ultimate os is
>posted here, the linux lynch mob mentality takes over, and we're
>burried by an article after another of vulgar flames. Even though the
>comparison was not posted to their group.

Well, don't crosspost needlessly (like your article is). You really
are a mental giant, aren't you? I'm keeping the crossposting on
because I want you to see this. 

>Of course, there is also the FANATIC MENTALITY, but that one is
>obvious.

From your statements, obviously.

>Observation #3:
>For a long time they kidded us about how NT is vaporware. The general
>consensus among them is that NT will never see the light of day, and
>our replies that it is coming out "soon" were laughed at. But look at
>what they are saying right now: Loadable device drivers... "soon",
>Drag and drop... "R6 is out any day now", Running ODS apps...
>"emulator is coming along nicely", Running Winodws apps... "WABI is
>almost here", ..etc. ..etc. What a joke!

NT is vaproware. Where is the shrink-wrap version? Egghead? Not!

The QIC-80 driver is loadable.  You can install it today, along with
your new Diamond SpeedStar NT drivers (not).

In case you don't know, xfm has a drag-and-drop interface, as well as
Motif.

Personally, I don't use the emulator, but it sure is amazing compared
to what it used to be. The shame is that MS software uses undocumented
programming hooks that make DOS and Windows very hard to duplicate
without a licen$ing agreement. This same proprietary rigging of DOS
is what has gotten MS in trouble with the FTC.

>Observation #4:
>Linux is inferior to DOS! How's that? Well, DOS has loadable device
>drivers, linux doesn't. Your printer and modem use the same IRQ? No
>problem in Windows, just don't use them at the same time. In linux,
>you have to use the modem a little, stop, recompile the kernel with
>the printer enabled and the modem disabled, use the printer a little,
>stop, recompile, use the modem, stop, ...etc. Two drivers that use the
>same IRQ cannot live in the same kernel, even if none of them is used!

DOS device drivers are so nice, they reduce the amount of memory so
you can't run Wolfenstein or TestDrive 3 while logged onto a network!
A bug in a Windows ATI driver is so good it will terminate Matlab 4.0!
DOS device drivers can access all of your memory so nothing is safe.
Happy now?

IRQ's in Linux are allocated. If your hardware IRQ's are screwed, they
won't work, period. The linux printer driver doesn't use an interrupt,
it's polled. I know, I wrote the original one, a while ago. I have a
modem, two serial ports, and a network card. Fix your hardware and
stop whining.

>Observation #5:
>Not only that linux doesn't support drag an drop, its users have no
>concept of what drag and drop is! Most of them think it's just cut and
>paste, as can be seen clearly in the "rebuttals".  The only way to get
>drag and drop in linux is to pay $299 (NT is less expensive, how
>ironic) to buy Motif, and virtually no Motif application makes use of
>it anyway, and you cannot drag and drop between Motif and Xaw
>applications.

Actually, while I use both Windoze and X, most applications in both
don't support dnd. What I really use is cut-and-paste, and that is
horribly broken in Windoze. Haven't MS heard of a cut buffer?

And how do you know what the price of NT will be before it's released?
Pity that some people trust MS press releases.

>Observation #6:
>Linux users have no idea what multimedia support is.  Multimedia
>support is NOT that the os is able to talk to a sound card!  DOS can
>do that. It is that the os has inherent layering facilities to do
>multimedia. To run a full motion picture clip or play a MIDI song via
>the sequencer in Windows, you just call a single API function (e.g.
>MciSendCommand).

Linux supports multimedia through X. You can play MPEG, FLI, GRASP, etc,
to your heart's content. MIT is making a killing doing interactive
video through X apps. With shared memory, you can run at full speeed
now.

>Observation #7:
>QIC-80 support is not in linux, nor is it ever likey to be. The
>general consensus among linux developers is that QIC-80 is simply
>unsuitable to multitasking environments, a claim that's obviously
>disproved by NT's support for QIC-80.

I don't know for sure how NT handles QIC-80. I do know that it is
tightly coupled to system timing (serial communication through
floppy select lines) and the best way to set up QIC-80 transfers
is to turn off the multitasking. That is the fool-proof way to meet the
timing specs. QIC-117 makes that abundantly clear. Read your copy.

>Observation #8:
>Q: What does linux do when it runs low on memmory? A: IT FALTERS! The
>only os I have seen that locks up when it runs low in memory. Every
>linux user must constantly watch for memory useage, if linux needs a
>few more kilobytes than are available, it doesn't complain, it just
>crawls to a halt before dying a miserable death, taking down the whole
>system with it.

Gee, Windows just dumps me out at the DOS prompt. Someone once said, if
your system swaps too much, it is the fault of the system administrator,
and you should get more memory. If you run out of swap, shame on
you.

>Need I say more? There is still lots to talk about: the flaky file
>system, the feeble networking, ..etc. ..etc.

I use the minix fs, extfs, and ext2fs, and have not had any problems
except those due to my own fumble fingers.

The networking is not feeble. It is new, written from scratch, and keeps
improving. MS has demonstrated it wouldn't know good networking code
if it hit them, and they refuse to admit it. Expect NT to have several
serious problems loosing network files.

>Linux users, get a clue! Your os is shit. And remember, we didn't
>start this.

This is what provoked me. Lacking any reasonable argument, you
resort to name-calling. Well, that really shows your maturity.
We're so impressed by your bold use of a four letter word!
Wow!

>-Bri

jim "get it right" wiegand

